properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An intense low pressure system near Sanikiluaq early this morning will track northeast into northern Quebec today. North winds will strengthen today with gusts to 70 or 80 km/h by late this afternoon. Strong north winds will continue tonight and into Tuesday morning. These strong winds will result in blowing snow with the potential for blizzard or near blizzard conditions. A gradual improvement will take place Tuesday afternoon and evening. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Maximum gusts: southeasterly 80 km/h, except between 100 and 120 km/h along parts of the coast prone to enhanced southeasterlies. Locations: along the west coast from St. George's Bay to Barr'd Harbour. Time span: this afternoon and evening. Remarks: The strongest wind gusts will begin in the St. George's Bay area late this afternoon and spread northward along the coast this evening. Winds will diminish by midnight as winds shift to southwesterly. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: High Water Level Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Higher than normal water levels are expected or occurring. Locations: southeast facing shorelines of the Acadian Peninsula south to Miramichi. Maximum water levels: exceeding highest astronomical tides. Maximum Wave height: 3 to 4 metres. Time span: Near high tide this afternoon. Remarks: coastal flooding due to large high tides, storm surge and some wave activity. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. For more information monitor Canadian Coast Guard radio or Weatheradio stations.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A Pacific storm will approach British Columbia tonight and Tuesday. Heavy snow and strong winds will combine to produce blowing snow across Pine Pass where 20 cm of snow will accumulate on Tuesday. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
